"color(98.6,91.0,76.6)", "color_r": 98.6}, {"content": "\u300a\u7aef\u5348\u7bc0\u7ced\u5b50\u300b\u4e2d\u83ef\u7cbd (\u8fb2\u66c6 5\u67085\u65e5)\nSticky rice dumplings\n*\nRice dumplings for dinner tonight, with a plate of steamed choysum. These bamboo leaf parcels are stuffed with glutinous rice, mung beans, red beans, marinated pork belly, salted egg yolk and dried shrimps. They are boiled for 2 hours, drained and cooled down then stored in refrigerator. To serve, reheat the dumplings in a steamer, unwrap the bamboo leaves, eat straight or dip with soy sauce or sugar. They are the traditional Chinese food for the Dragon Boat Festival (Tuen Ng Festival). Zongzi is rice with beans, fruits, or meats wrapped in leaves and then boiled for an hour. The result is DELISH! Dreamfield is part of PEAC, Pesticide Eco-Alternatives Center, an NGO here in Kunming that works with farmers to investigate the potential harms and effects of chemical pesticides and fertilizers. I recently started working with them and they ROCK!\n__\n#dragonboatfestival #zongzi #peac #dreamfield #kunming #yunnan #china #diy #\u7aef\u5348 #\u7cbd\u5b50 #\u6606\u660e #\u4e91\u5357 #\u4e2d\u56fd #\u624b\u5de5", "color_g": 53.2, "color_b": 47.0, "source": "#\u7aef\u5348", "time": "2017-05-24T12:04:54+00:00", "img_link": "https://scontent-tpe1-1.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/c0.135.1080.1080/18646248_1810179122632686_5719796892284485632_n.jpg", "href_link": "/p/BUeXS3MjfKv/?tagged=%E7%AB%AF%E5%8D%88", "detail_infos": "{\"version\": \"1.0\", \"title\": \"\\ud83d\\udc09 in honor of Dragon Boat Festival (\\u7aef\\u5348) we had a zongzi making party at Dreamfield, a grocery store that connects local farmers in Yunnan with consumers in Kunming. Zongzi is rice with beans, fruits, or meats wrapped in leaves and then boiled for an hour. The result is DELISH! Dreamfield is part of PEAC, Pesticide Eco-Alternatives Center, an NGO here in Kunming that works with farmers to investigate the potential harms and effects of chemical pesticides and fertilizers. Dragon Boat Festival\n*\nMade some rice dumplings today. These bamboo leaf parcels are stuffed with glutinous rice, mung beans, red beans, marinated pork belly, salted egg yolk and dried shrimps. They are boiled for 2 hours, drained and cooled down then stored in refrigerator. To serve, reheat the dumplings in a steamer, unwrap the bamboo leaves, eat straight or dip with soy sauce or sugar. They are the traditional Chinese food for the Dragon Boat Festival (Tuen Ng Festival). is held on the 5th of May. Although originally from China, Japan has a different meaning to the festival. The Tango-no-sekku is a festival to cleanse women that are working in rice fields, of evil spirits, for good health, and to keep disaster away. As shobu (leaves of the Iris flower) and shobu (fighting spirit) sound phonetically like each other, the shobu leaves which are sword-like in shape and hence the festival name Tango-no-sekku (also called Shobu-no-sekku), and it became a festival for boys to pray for good health.\n\n\u7aef\u5348\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066\u8a73\u3057\u304f\u306f\u3053\u3061\u3089\nAnd is held on the 5th of May. Although originally from China, Japan has a different meaning to the festival. The Tango-no-sekku is a festival to cleanse women that are working in rice fields, of evil spirits, for good health, and to keep disaster away. As shobu (leaves of the Iris flower) and shobu (fighting spirit) sound phonetically like each other, the shobu leaves which are sword-like in shape and hence the festival name Tango-no-sekku (also called Shobu-no-sekku), and it became a festival for boys to pray for good health.\\n\\n\\u7aef\\u5348\\u306b\\u3064\\u3044\\u3066\\u8a73\\u3057\\u304f\\u306f\\u3053\\u3061\\u3089\\nAnd more...\\nhttp://koyomibako.com/may/\\n\\n#\\u7aef\\u5348#\\u4e94\\u6708#\\u7690\\u6708#\\u83d6\\u84b2#\\u3042\\u3084\\u3081#\\u67cf\\u9905#\\u515c#\\u7cbd#\\u9bc9\\u306e\\u307c\\u308a#\\u9bc9\\u5e5f#Boysfestival#Tango#helmet#carpstreamer#Iris#May\\n#\\u82b1\\u7d50\\u3073#\\u5ba4\\u793c#\\u884c\\u4e8b#\\u5e74\\u4e2d\\u884c\\u4e8b#Japanese#Japaneseculture#display#wa#wabisabi#Japan#Koyomibako#\\u66a6\\u7bb1\", \"author_name\": \"koyomibako\", \"author_url\": \"https://www.instagram.com/koyomibako\", \"author_id\": 2012695712, \"media_id\": \"1507680192737685607_2012695712\", \"provider_name\": \"Instagram\", \"provider_url\": \"https://www.instagram.com\", \"type\": \"rich\", \"width\": 658, \"height\": null, \"html\": \"\\u003cblockquote class=\\\"instagram-media\\\" data-instgrm-captioned data-instgrm-version=\\\"7\\\" style=\\\" background:#FFF; Although originally from China, Japan has a different meaning to the festival. The Tango-no-sekku is a festival to cleanse women that are working in rice fields, of evil spirits, for good health, and to keep disaster away. is held on the 5th of May. Although originally from China, Japan has a different meaning to the festival. The Tango-no-sekku is a festival to cleanse women that are working in rice fields, of evil spirits, for good health, and to keep disaster away. As shobu (leaves of the Iris flower) and shobu (fighting spirit) sound phonetically like each other, the shobu leaves which are sword-like in shape and hence the festival name Tango-no-sekku (also called Shobu-no-sekku), and it became a festival for boys to pray for good health.\\n\\n\\u7aef\\u5348\\u306b\\u3064\\u3044\\u3066\\u8a73\\u3057\\u304f\\u306f\\u3053\\u3061\\u3089\\nAnd more...\\nhttp://koyomibako.com/may/\\n\\n#\\u7aef\\u5348#\\u4e94\\u6708#\\u7690\\u6708#\\u83d6\\u84b2#\\u3042\\u3084\\u3081#\\u67cf\\u9905#\\u515c#\\u7cbd#\\u9bc9\\u306e\\u307c\\u308a#\\u9bc9\\u5e5f#Boysfestival#Tango#helmet#carpstreamer#Iris#May\\n#\\u82b1\\u7d50\\u3073#\\u5ba4\\u793c#\\u884c\\u4e8b#\\u5e74\\u4e2d\\u884c\\u4e8b#Japanese#Japaneseculture#display#wa#wabisabi#Japan#Koyomibako#\\u66a6\\u7bb1\", \"author_name\": \"koyomibako\", \"author_url\": \"https://www.instagram.com/koyomibako\", \"author_id\": 2012695712, \"media_id\": \"1507679977150550263_2012695712\", \"provider_name\": \"Instagram\", \"provider_url\": \"https://www.instagram.com\", \"type\": \"rich\", \"width\": 658, \"height\": null, \"html\": \"\\u003cblockquote class=\\\"instagram-media\\\" data-instgrm-captioned data-instgrm-version=\\\"7\\\" style=\\\" background:#FFF; Although originally from China, Japan has a different meaning to the festival. The Tango-no-sekku is a festival to cleanse women that are working in rice fields, of evil spirits, for good health, and to keep disaster away. As shobu (leaves of the Iris flower) and shobu (fighting spirit) sound phonetically like each other, the shobu leaves which are sword-like in shape and hence the festival name Tango-no-sekku (also called Shobu-no-sekku), and it became a festival for boys to pray for good health. \\u7aef\\u5348\\u306b\\u3064\\u3044\\u3066\\u8a73\\u3057\\u304f\\u306f\\u3053\\u3061\\u3089 And more... http://koyomibako.com/may/ #\\u7aef\\u5348#\\u4e94\\u6708#\\u7690\\u6708#\\u83d6\\u84b2#\\u3042\\u3084\\u3081#\\u67cf\\u9905#\\u515c#\\u7cbd#\\u9bc9\\u306e\\u307c\\u308a#\\u9bc9\\u5e5f#Boysfestival#Tango#helmet#carpstreamer#Iris#May #\\u82b1\\u7d50\\u3073#\\u5ba4\\u793c#\\u884c\\u4e8b#\\u5e74\\u4e2d\\u884c\\u4e8b#Japanese#Japaneseculture#display#wa#wabisabi#Japan#Koyomibako#\\u66a6\\u7bb1\\u003c/a\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e \\u003cp style=\\\" color:#c9c8cd; Although originally from China, Japan has a different meaning to the festival. The Tango-no-sekku is a festival to cleanse women that are working in rice fields, of evil spirits, for good health, and to keep disaster away. As shobu (leaves of the Iris flower) and shobu (fighting spirit) sound phonetically like each other, the shobu leaves which are sword-like in shape and hence the festival name Tango-no-sekku (also The Tango-no-sekku is a festival to cleanse women that are working in rice fields, of evil spirits, for good health, and to keep disaster away.
